thread.title: US rates decision pushes $A lower

title: US rates decision pushes $A lower
text:
Mon, Sep 21, 2015, 12:30 PM AEST - Australia Markets close in 3 hrs 30 mins US rates decision pushes $A lower AAP â€“ 16 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar has plunged two thirds of a US cent as the negative fallout from last week's US interest rate decision continues. 
At 1200 AEST on Monday, the local unit was trading at 71.68 US cents, down from 72.28 cents on Friday. 
At the end of last week, the US Federal Reserve surprised some in the market by holding off on a much anticipated interest rate hike, leaving investors uncertain of the outlook for the US economy. 
Fed chair Janet Yellen cited concern about the slowdown in China and its impact on the US economy as the reason for not raising the rise. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* 71.68 US cents, from 72.28 cents on Friday 
* 85.91 Japanese yen, from 86.47 yen 
* 63.41 euro cents, from 63.38 euro cents 
* 112.45 New Zealand cents, from 113.17 NZ cents 
* 46.14 British pence, from 46.39 pence 
Government bond yields: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.876pct, from 1.897pct on Friday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.800pct, from 2.844pct 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* The December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.240 (implying a yield of 2.760 per cent), up from 97.190 (2.810 per cent) on Friday. 
* The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.110 (1.890 per cent), up from 98.100 (1.900 per cent). 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session, bond market closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
